  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The City Tower
  author: Lim Yujung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alone I climb the tower above the border city—
    Weiya's words echo still.
    Evening mist and sparse rain cannot contain my sorrow—
    Li Chengji knew this well.
    Blue mountains remain my constant companions—
    Zheng Yan spoke truly.
    White hair, without mercy, now crowns my head—
    Luo E understood.
    With zither and wine cup, laughter flows between us—
    Ye Buqi showed the way.
    Do not refuse to pause your carriage and horses here—
    Yang Pan invited us to linger.
    The tower's shadow dances upon the river moon—
    Li Li saw this beauty.
    In the depth of night, autumn's voice sings—
    The cricket's cry, says Luo Yin.
    I buy wine and Tao Ling alone grows drunk—
    Zi Zhan knew such freedom.
    I write my poem, and perhaps Hui Lian's wandering is allowed—
    Yang Pan granted permission.
    Idly I carve the streamside stones into a game board—
    Zi Xi found peace thus.
    Laughing, I break the flowering branch for wine measures—
    Le Tian cherished such moments.
    All things yield to fate, known from the start—
    Gong Ji grasped this truth.
    Why scheme for human affairs when all is already written?—
    Jing Gong asks us this.
  footnotes:
    - This poem is a collective work in which each couplet is attributed to a different classical Chinese poet or figure, creating a dialogue across centuries about contemplation, acceptance, and the transience of human concern.
    - The references to Tao Ling (Tao Yuanming), Hui Lian, and other classical figures invoke their legacies of poetic freedom and philosophical wisdom.
    - The progression moves from solitary observation through social pleasures to ultimate philosophical acceptance of fate, mirroring the journey of understanding that comes with age and reflection.
